k.com/photo.php?fbid=10157141754196287&set=a.9568151286&type=3&theater]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n|Narrator\n|Ron Roy Productions<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/ron.roy.10/videos/10157371255846287/]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2010\n|Heartland USA (TV Commercial)<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10157141754196287&set=a.9568151286&type=3&theater]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n|Narrator\n|Ron Roy Productions<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/ron.roy.10/videos/vb.565381286/10150221509101287/?type=3]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2011\n|''Jingle Bells Chicken''<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IoagyKrSUcQ]</ref>\n|Hollywood Chicken\n|Ron Roy Productions\n|-\n|2012\n|''Jesus Face in the Clouds'' (Documentary)\n|Host\n|Ron Roy Productions\n|-\n|2018\n|''David Cassidy: The Last Session''<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/ron.roy.10/videos/vb.565381286/10156242957981287/?type=3]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n|Himself\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0\n|[[A&E Networks|A & E]]<ref>[http://www.facebook.com/ron.roy.10/videos/vb.565381286/10156242957981287/?type=3]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Producer/Director/Cinematographer===\n* 1984 \u2013 Thrill Of The Kill (Music Video)[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aUL_zBoBlro ]\n*1985 \u2013 [[Hollywood Cross|The Hollywood Cross (documentary)]]\n*1986 \u2013 Tranquility (video documentary)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YC5b0HE8boY&t=1236s]\n*1985 \u2013 Body Map (Fashion Rock Video)\n*1987 \u2013 Fleece Chemise (Fashion Rock Video)\n* 1987 \u2013 Moodtape's Energy (video) (producer/director)\n*1987 \u2013 Fleece Chemise (Fashion Rock Video)\n* 1987 \u2013 Floral Fantasy (video documentary)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yo0V05FRAgc]\n* 1988 \u2013 Autumn Whispers\u2026 Winter Dreams[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iZ7u0By-7Pg]\n* 1988 \u2013 1991 Stand-up Comics Take a Stand (TV Movie) [https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151932435546287&set=a.476062181286&type=3&theater]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}\n* 1991 \u2013 Contemporary Christmas (video documentary)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tw2hHh6BcCM]\n* 1991 \u2013 Moodtapes: Ocean Reflections (video documentary short)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rbi2il5qrdE]\n* 1992 \u2013 Moodtapes: Natural Environments \u2013 Whispering Waters (video documentary)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ULNcgOOJ3kI]\n* 1993 \u2013 Romantic Classics by Firelight (video documentary)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aX-GqIT2fVU]\n* 1993 \u2013 Pacific Surf (video documentary)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oKNAz0E-pxU]\n*1995 \u2013 L'Image Fashion Party Video[https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151932491226287&set=a.476062181286&type=3&theater]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}\n* 1996 \u2013 [[Nicole Conn|Cynara: Poetry in Motion]] (cinematography)\n* 1997 \u2013 Moodtapes: Moments \u2013 Serenity (video documentary)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-WsYVZ4p50s]\n* 1998 \u2013 Nature's Bouquet (video documentary)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yo0V05FRAgc]\n* 2003 \u2013 The Yule Log HD (TV Movie)[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0925147/]\n*2006 \u2013 The Future Is Now (documentary)\u00a0 \u00a0 \n*2006 \u2013 Relax with Moodtapes (iTunes Podcast)[https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/relax-with-moodtapes/id152719182]\n*2009 \u2013 Pacific Surf (iPhone App)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lv-ybz9_zWI&t=533s]\n*2010 \u2013 Christmas Magic (iPhone App)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NQXFPaDKRBs]\n*2011 \u2013 Jingle Bells Chicken (Christmas Music Video)\n*2011 \u2013 Clair de Lune (Relaxation Music Video)\n*2011 \u2013 Danny Boy (Relaxation Video)\n*2011 \u2013 Sizzlin' Christmas (Christmas Rock Video)\n*2012 \u2013 Pacific Blue (Music Video)[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DJg5U1-0gH4]\n*2012 \u2013 Serenity Prayer (Motivational Video)\n*2012 \u2013 Jesus Face In The Clouds (Documentary)\n* 2013 \u2013 Viewzzz relaxation music videos (producer/director)\n*2013 \u2013 Tribute To America (Patriotic Rock Video)\n*2013 \u2013 Snowy White Christmas (Music Video)\n*2014 \u2013 Oregon Waters (Nature Relaxation Video)\n*2014 \u2013 Impressions of Winter (Music Video)[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p5UeECPOJ3Q]\n*2014 \u2013 Angel of the Mountain Stream (Motivational Video)\n*2018 \u2013 [[Wounded Warrior Project|Horses and Heroes (documentary)]]\n*2018 \u2013 Drift Away (Nature/Relaxation Video)\n*2019\u00a0\u2013 Amazing\u00a0Grace Medley (Religious Music Video)   \n*2019 \u2013 [[Wounded Warrior Project|Horses & Heroes II (documentary)]]\n\n===Television===\nRon Roy and his video productions have been featured on national television programs: ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'', ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'', [[Fox TV]], [[MTV]], [[VH-1]], [[The Family Channel (American TV network, founded 1980)|The Family Channel]], ''[[The 700 Club]]'', [[The Business Channel]], ''[[CBS Morning Show]]'', [[CNN]], ''[[Today (American TV program)|The Today Show]]'' etc.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n* Hollywood Angel Award (1985)<ref name=\"cross\" />\n* Seven International Telly Awards (1992 -1995)<ref>[http://www.tellyawards.com]</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151932433326287&set=a.476062181286&type=3&theater]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10157364839216287&set=a.51410751286&type=3&theater]{{Primary source inline|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n* New York International Fashion Video Award\n* International Aegis Award (2006)<ref name=\"aegis\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aegisawards.com/winners_list.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19981202074358/http://www.aegisawards.com/winners_list.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 2, 1998 |title=Winners & Finalists |year=2006 |website=aegisawards.com |publisher=Aegis Awards |accessdate=October 13, 2013 }}</ref> \n* Davey Award (2006, silver winner)<ref name=\"davey\">{{cite web \n|url=https://www.daveyawards.com/winners/list/?l=R&event=2&category=&award=S&form=2\n|title= Silver Winners\n|year=2006\n|website=daveyawards.com\n|publisher=Davey Awards\n|accessdate=October 13, 2013}}</ref>\n* International [[Accolade Competition|Accolade Award]] (2009)<ref name=\"accolade\">{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.accoladecompetition.org/WinnersAccoladeDeadline112709.pdf\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131001012832/http://www.accoladecompetition.org/WinnersAccoladeDeadline112709.pdf\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = October 1, 2013\n |title      = Award of Merit Winners. Videography\n |year       = 2009\n |website    = accoladecompetition.org\n |publisher  = Accolade Competition\n |accessdate = October 13, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.jesussmilesonus.com/About_Ron_Roy.html Personal website]\n* {{IMDb name|0747171}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roy, Ron}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Houston]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:People from Houston]]\n[[Category:American cinematographers]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Texas]]\n", "name_user": "Gonnym", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ron_Roy_(producer)"}
{"title_page": "Everard Baths", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Everard Baths\n| image = Eveard-bath1.jpg\n| caption = Baths in 2009\n| coordinates = {{Coord|40.7454|-73.9892|region:US-NY_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| building_type = Bath house\n| address = 28 West 28th Street\n| location = [[New York City]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| opened_date = {{Start date|1888}}\n| closing_date = {{End date|1986|04}}\n| renovation_date = 1977\n| facilities =private rooms, wet and dry steamrooms, pool\n}}\nThe '''Everard Baths''' or '''Everard Spa Turkish Bathhouse''' was a [[gay bathhouse]] at 28 West 28th Street in [[New York City]] that operated from 1888 to 1986. The venue occupied an adaptively reused church building and was the site of a deadly fire.\n\n==History==\nEverard Baths was a [[Turkish bath]] founded by financier James Everard in 1888 in a former church building, designed in a typical late-nineteenth-century [[Victorian architectural style|Victorian]] [[Romanesque Revival architectural style]]. James Everard who operated the Everard brewery on 135th Street converted it to a bathhouse in 1888. Everard's bathhouse was intended for general health and fitness.<ref name=churches>J. Russiello, ''A Sympathetic Planning Hierarchy for Redundant Churches: A Comparison of Continued Use and Reuse in Denmark, England and the United States of America]'' (MSc [[Conservation of Historic Buildings]], [[University of Bath]], 2008), p.383.</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 1898, a soldier was found dead in his room at the baths and gas was suspected.<ref name=\"Colter1996\"/><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Baltimore and Ohio Southwestern|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1898/11/29/102570279.pdf|date=29 November 1898|title=Ex-Soldier Killed by Gas | format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nOn January 5, 1919, the [[New York Society for the Suppression of Vice]] encouraged a police raid in which the manager and nine customers were arrested for lewd behavior. It was raided again in 1920 with 15 arrests.<ref name=Chauncey1995 >{{citation | last=Chauncey | first=George | year=1995 | title=Gay New York: Gender, Urban Culture, and the Making of the Gay Male World, 1890-1940 | edition=reprint | publisher=Basic Books | isbn=978-0-465-02621-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M27vzxO0kd0C&cd=1}}</ref>\n\nIt was patronized largely by homosexuals by the 1920s and became the community's preeminent social venue from the 1930s onward.<ref name=Stein2004>{{harv|Stein|2004|p=90}}</ref> It was patronized by gay men before the 1920s and by the 1930s had a reputation as \"classiest, safest, and best known of the baths,\" eventually picking up the nickname \"Everhard\".<ref name=neilmiller>{{harv|Miller|1995|p=143}}</ref>\n\nThe entrance was lit by two green lamps giving it, according to patrons, the appearance of a police precinct and giving rise to speculation that it was owned for a period by the [[Patrolmen's Benevolent Association of the City of New York]] (a claim that was vehemently denied after patrons died in a 1977 fire).\n\n[[Emlyn Williams]] described a visit in 1927:\n\n:Up some stairs at a desk an ashen bored man in shirtsleeves produced a ledger crammed with illegible scrawls. I added mine, paid my dollar, was handed a key, towel and robe, hung the key on my wrist and mounted to a large floor as big as a warehouse and as high: intersecting rows of private rooms each windowless cell dark except from the glimmer from above through wire-netting shredded with dust and containing a narrow workhouse bed...[he later heard] a casual whisper, a sigh lighter than thistle-down, a smothered moan. Then appeasement: the snap of a lighter as two strangers sat back for a smoke and polite murmured small talk, such as they might exchange in a gym.<ref name=Colter1996 >{{citation | last1=Colter | first1=Ephen Glenn | year=1996 | title=Policing public sex: queer politics and the future of AIDS activism | last2=Bedfellows | first2=Dangerous | editor1=Ephen Glenn Colter | editor2=Dangerous Bedfellows | publisher=[[South End Press]] | isbn=978-0-89608-549-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FqMoLytiNlUC}}</ref>\n\nAmong the documented patrons were [[Alfred Lunt]], [[Clifton Webb]], [[No\u00ebl Coward]], [[Lorenz Hart]], [[Truman Capote]], [[Charles James (designer)|Charles James]], [[Gore Vidal]] and [[Rudolf Nureyev]].<ref name=McCourt2004 >{{citation | last=McCourt | first=James | year=2004 | title=Queer street: rise and fall of an American culture, 1947-1985 : excursions in the mind of the life | publisher=W.W. Norton | isbn=978-0-393-05051-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w095qAb2BsgC&cd=1}}</ref> [[Truman Capote]] and [[Ned Rorem]] wrote about their visits.<ref name=Plimpton1997 >{{citation | last=Plimpton | first=George | year=1997 | title=Truman Capote: in which various friends, enemies, acquaintances, and detractors recall his turbulent career | publisher=Nan A. Talese/Doubleday | isbn=978-0-385-23249-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XGBoAAAAMAAJ&cd=1}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 1977, nine patrons (ages 17 to 40) were killed in a fire: seven from smoke inhalation, one from respiratory burns, and one who had jumped from an upper floor. Contributing factors were the deteriorating conditions and the lack of sprinklers.<ref name=Bronstein>Scott Bronstein, \u201c4 New York Bathhouses Still Operate Under City\u2019s Program of Inspections,\u201d ''[[The New York Times]]'' (3 May 1987).</ref> Firefighters said they were thwarted in rescue efforts by paneling covering the windows. Between 80 and 100 patrons left the building; the indefinite number was because the club did not have registration at the time. Most of the victims were identified by friends rather than family.<ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F10816F83E5F15768FDDAE0A94DD405B878BF1D3 9 Killed in Bath Fire Identified by Friends - New York Times - May 27, 1977]</ref> Accounts said costs were $5 for a locker or $7 for a cubicle ($6 and $9.25 on weekends).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bitterqueen.typepad.com/history_of_gay_bars_in_ne/2007/12/the-everard-bat.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204012639/http://bitterqueen.typepad.com/history_of_gay_bars_in_ne/2007/12/the-everard-bat.html |archive-date=2008-12-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDespite total destruction of the top two floors, the two floors were rebuilt, and the baths reopened.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.colors-of-leather.com/Lthr%20bars/Bars%202nd%20page/EFG/Everard%20Baths.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204003654/http://www.colors-of-leather.com/Lthr%20bars/Bars%202nd%20page/EFG/Everard%20Baths.htm |archive-date=2008-12-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, it was closed in April 1986 by New York City mayor [[Ed Koch]] during the city's campaign to close such venues during the AIDS epidemic.<ref name=Bronstein/>\n\n==Popular culture==\n[[Michael Rumaker]] wrote a book ''A Day and a Night at the Baths'', devoted totally to the baths.<ref>A Day and a Night at the Baths by Michael Rumaker Grey Fox Press (1979) {{ISBN|0-912516-44-5}}</ref>\n\nThe bath is described in the novels ''[[Dancer from the Dance]]'' by [[Andrew Holleran]],<ref name=Holleran2001 >{{citation | last=Holleran | first=Andrew | year=2001 | title=Dancer from the dance: a novel | edition=reprint | publisher=Perennial | isbn=978-0-06-093706-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QCDrJZyrW-oC&cd=1}}</ref> ''[[Faggots (novel)|Faggots]]'' by [[Larry Kramer]], and ''Now Voyagers'' by [[James McCourt (writer)|James McCourt]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://gaytubs.com/lengendary.htm\n\n{{Portal bar|LGBT|New York City|Human sexuality}}\n\n[[Category:1888 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:May 1977 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:1986 disestablishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Building fires in New York City]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Burned buildings and structures in the United States]]\n[[Category:Churches in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Closed churches in New York City]]\n[[Category:Former churches in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Gay bathhouses in New York City]]\n[[Category:LGBT history in New York City]]\n[[Category:Romanesque Revival architecture in New York City]]\n[[Category:Commercial building fires]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Everard Baths\n| image = Eveard-bath1.jpg\n| caption = Baths in 2009\n| coordinates = {{Coord|40.7454|-73.9892|region:US-NY_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| building_type = Bath house\n| address = 28 West 28th Street\n| location = [[New York City]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| opened_date = {{Start date|1888}}\n| closing_date = {{End date|1986|04}}\n| renovation_date = 1977\n| facilities =private rooms, wet and dry steamrooms, pool\n}}\nThe '''Everard Baths''' or '''Everard Spa Turkish Bathhouse''' was a [[gay bathhouse]] at 28 West 28th Street in [[New York City]] that operated from 1888 to 1986. The venue occupied an adaptively reused church building and was the site of a deadly fire.\n\n==History==\nEverard Baths was a [[Turkish bath]] founded by financier James Everard in 1888 in a former church building, designed in a typical late-nineteenth-century [[Victorian architectural style|Victorian]] [[Romanesque Revival architectural style]]. James Everard who operated the Everard brewery on 135th Street converted it to a bathhouse in 1888. Everard's bathhouse was intended for general health and fitness.<ref name=churches>J. Russiello, ''A Sympathetic Planning Hierarchy for Redundant Churches: A Comparison of Continued Use and Reuse in Denmark, England and the United States of America]'' (MSc [[Conservation of Historic Buildings]], [[University of Bath]], 2008), p.383.</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 1898, a soldier was found dead in his room at the baths and gas was suspected.<ref name=\"Colter1996\"/><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Baltimore and Ohio Southwestern|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1898/11/29/102570279.pdf|date=29 November 1898|title=Ex-Soldier Killed by Gas | format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nOn January 5, 1919, the [[New York Society for the Suppression of Vice]] encouraged a police raid in which the manager and nine customers were arrested for lewd behavior. It was raided again in 1920 with 15 arrests.<ref name=Chauncey1995 >{{citation | last=Chauncey | first=George | year=1995 | title=Gay New York: Gender, Urban Culture, and the Making of the Gay Male World, 1890-1940 | edition=reprint | publisher=Basic Books | isbn=978-0-465-02621-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M27vzxO0kd0C&cd=1}}</ref>\n\nIt was patronized largely by homosexuals by the 1920s and became the community's preeminent social venue from the 1930s onward.<ref name=Stein2004>{{harv|Stein|2004|p=90}}</ref> It was patronized by gay men before the 1920s and by the 1930s had a reputation as \"classiest, safest, and best known of the baths,\" eventually picking up the nickname \"Everhard\".<ref name=neilmiller>{{harv|Miller|1995|p=143}}</ref>\n\nThe entrance was lit by two green lamps giving it, according to patrons, the appearance of a police precinct and giving rise to speculation that it was owned for a period by the [[Patrolmen's Benevolent Association of the City of New York]] (a claim that was vehemently denied after patrons died in a 1977 fire).\n\n[[Emlyn Williams]] described a visit in 1927:\n\n:Up some stairs at a desk an ashen bored man in shirtsleeves produced a ledger crammed with illegible scrawls. I added mine, paid my dollar, was handed a key, towel and robe, hung the key on my wrist and mounted to a large floor as big as a warehouse and as high: intersecting rows of private rooms each windowless cell dark except from the glimmer from above through wire-netting shredded with dust and containing a narrow workhouse bed...[he later heard] a casual whisper, a sigh lighter than thistle-down, a smothered moan. Then appeasement: the snap of a lighter as two strangers sat back for a smoke and polite murmured small talk, such as they might exchange in a gym.<ref name=Colter1996 >{{citation | last1=Colter | first1=Ephen Glenn | year=1996 | title=Policing public sex: queer politics and the future of AIDS activism | last2=Bedfellows | first2=Dangerous | editor1=Ephen Glenn Colter | editor2=Dangerous Bedfellows | publisher=[[South End Press]] | isbn=978-0-89608-549-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FqMoLytiNlUC}}</ref>\n\nAmong the documented patrons were [[Alfred Lunt]], [[Clifton Webb]], [[No\u00ebl Coward]], [[Lorenz Hart]], [[Truman Capote]], [[Charles James (designer)|Charles James]], [[Gore Vidal]] and [[Rudolf Nureyev]].<ref name=McCourt2004 >{{citation | last=McCourt | first=James | year=2004 | title=Queer street: rise and fall of an American culture, 1947-1985 : excursions in the mind of the life | publisher=W.W. Norton | isbn=978-0-393-05051-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w095qAb2BsgC&cd=1}}</ref> [[Truman Capote]] and [[Ned Rorem]] wrote about their visits.<ref name=Plimpton1997 >{{citation | last=Plimpton | first=George | year=1997 | title=Truman Capote: in which various friends, enemies, acquaintances, and detractors recall his turbulent career | publisher=Nan A. Talese/Doubleday | isbn=978-0-385-23249-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XGBoAAAAMAAJ&cd=1}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 1977, nine patrons (ages 17 to 40) were killed in a fire: seven from smoke inhalation, one from respiratory burns, and one who had jumped from an upper floor. Contributing factors were the deteriorating conditions and the lack of sprinklers.<ref name=Bronstein>Scott Bronstein, \u201c4 New York Bathhouses Still Operate Under City\u2019s Program of Inspections,\u201d ''[[The New York Times]]'' (3 May 1987).</ref> Firefighters said they were thwarted