:Works based on Doctor Who|Comics]]\n[[Category:Comics based on television series]]\n[[Category:Comics about time travel]]\n", "name_user": "McrPhilosophy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:improving references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Doctor_comic_stories"}
{"title_page": "Aveline de Forz, Countess of Aumale", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|consort= yes\n|name= Aveline de Forz\n|image= \n|succession= Countess of Aumale<br />Lady of Holderness\n|reign = \n|spouse= [[Edmund Crouchback, 1st Earl of Lancaster|Edmund ''Crouchback'', 1st Earl of Lancaster]]<br />m. 1269; dec. 1274\n|issue= \n|house=[[House of Plantagenet]] ''(by marriage)''\n|father= [[William de Forz, 4th Earl of Albemarle]]\n|mother= [[Isabella de Fortibus, Countess of Devon]]\n|birth_date= 20 January 1259\n|death_date= {{Death date|1274|11|10|df=yes}} (15 years)\n}}\n'''Aveline de Forz''', '''Countess of Aumale''' and '''Lady of Holderness''' (20 January 1259 \u2013 10 November 1274) was an English noblewoman. A great heiress, in 1269 she was married to [[Edmund Crouchback, 1st Earl of Lancaster]], the second son of [[Henry III of England]]. She died five years later, and the marriage produced no children.\n\n==Life==\nAveline de Forz was born on 20 January 1259 at [[Burstwick]] in [[Holderness]]. Her parents were [[William de Forz, 4th Earl of Albemarle]] and [[Isabella de Fortibus, Countess of Devon]].{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=75}}\n\n===Marriage===\n[[Eleanor of Provence|Queen Eleanor]], the consort of [[Henry III of England]], arranged the marriage between Aveline and their second son [[Edmund Crouchback, 1st Earl of Lancaster]]. Eleanor negotiated with Aveline's mother Isabella and grandmother [[Amice de Clare|Amice]] to secure the alliance.{{sfn|Hilton|2010|p=184}}  On 8 or 9 April 1269, Aveline was married to Edmund at [[Westminster Abbey]].{{sfn|Lloyd|2004}} Given that Aveline was only ten years old,{{sfn|Spencer|2014|page=14}} the marriage was not consummated until 1273, when she turned fourteen.{{sfn|Blank|2007|page=150}} With marriage to the great heiress, the already wealthy Edmund hoped to gain the earldoms of Devon and Aumale as well as the lordships of Holderness and the Isle of Wight.{{sfn|Lloyd|2004}}{{sfn|Spencer|2014|page=14}} Her last surviving brother, Thomas, died in 1269, and she inherited his titles, becoming [[Counts and dukes of Aumale#Aumale in the English peerage|Countess of Aumale]].{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=75}} Her lands fell into King Henry's custody.{{sfn|Spencer|2014|page=28}} However, Aveline died on 10 November 1274 at [[Stockwell]], [[Surrey]],{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=76}} which prevented Edmund from inheriting the lands.{{sfn|Lloyd|2004}} They had no children.{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=76}}\n\nAveline was buried in [[Westminster Abbey]], the first tomb to be placed in its new church.{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=76}} The historian [[Peter Coss]] has called the tombs of her and [[Eleanor of Castile]] \"two of the finest female effigies of the thirteenth century.\"{{sfn|Coss|1998|page=76}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Works cited\n* {{Cite book |title=Virgin: The Untouched History |first=Hanne |last=Blank |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=2007 |isbn=1596910119 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=The Lady in Medieval England 1000-1500 |first=Peter R. |last=Coss |authorlink=Peter Coss |publisher=Sutton Publishing |year=1998 |isbn=0788197886 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Queens Consort: England's Medieval Queens from Eleanor of Aquitaine to Elizabeth of York |first=Lisa|last=Hilton |publisher=Pegasus Classics|year=2010 |isbn=1605981052 |ref=harv}}\n*{{ODNBweb|last=Lloyd |first=Simon |title=Edmund, first earl of Lancaster and first earl of Leicester (1245\u20131296) |year=2004 |id=8504}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Nobility and Kingship in Medieval England |first=Andrew |last=Spencer |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2014 |isbn=110702675X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Alison|last=Weir |authorlink=Alison Weir|title=Britain's Royal Families, The Complete Genealogy|publisher=Vintage Books |year=2008 |isbn=978-0099539735 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{succession box | title= [[Earl of Aumale|Countess of Aumale]] | before=[[Thomas de Forz, 4th Earl of Aumale|Thomas de Forz]] | after=''Title defunct'' | years=1269&ndash;1274}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aumale, Aveline de Forz, Countess of}}\n[[Category:1259 births]]\n[[Category:1274 deaths]]\n[[Category:English countesses]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Earls of Albemarle]]\n[[Category:13th-century English people]]\n[[Category:13th-century English women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|consort= yes\n|name= Aveline de Forz\n|image= \n|succession= Countess of Aumale<br />Lady of Holderness\n|reign = \n|spouse= [[Edmund Crouchback, 1st Earl of Lancaster|Edmund ''Crouchback'', 1st Earl of Lancaster]]<br />m. 1269; dec. 1274\n|issue= \n|house=[[House of Plantagenet]] ''(by marriage)''\n|father= [[William de Forz, 4th Earl of Albemarle]]\n|mother= [[Isabella de Fortibus, Countess of Devon]]\n|birth_date= 20 January 1259\n|death_date= {{Death date|1274|11|10|df=yes}} (15 years)\n}}\n'''Aveline de Forz''', '''Countess of Aumale''' and '''Lady of Holderness''' (20 January 1259 \u2013 10 November 1274) was an English noblewoman. A great heiress, in 1269 she was married to [[Edmund Crouchback, 1st Earl of Lancaster]], the second son of [[Henry III of England]]. She died five years later, and the marriage produced no issue.\n\n==Life==\nAveline de Forz was born on 20 January 1259 at [[Burstwick]] in [[Holderness]]. Her parents were [[William de Forz, 4th Earl of Albemarle]] and [[Isabella de Fortibus, Countess of Devon]].{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=75}}\n\n===Marriage===\n[[Eleanor of Provence|Queen Eleanor]], the consort of [[Henry III of England]], arranged the marriage between Aveline and their second son [[Edmund Crouchback, 1st Earl of Lancaster]]. Eleanor negotiated with Aveline's mother Isabella and grandmother [[Amice de Clare|Amice]] to secure the alliance.{{sfn|Hilton|2010|p=184}}  On 8 or 9 April 1269, Aveline was married to Edmund at [[Westminster Abbey]].{{sfn|Lloyd|2004}} Given that Aveline was only ten years old,{{sfn|Spencer|2014|page=14}} the marriage was not consummated until 1273, when she turned fourteen.{{sfn|Blank|2007|page=150}} With marriage to the great heiress, the already wealthy Edmund hoped to gain the earldoms of Devon and Aumale as well as the lordships of Holderness and the Isle of Wight.{{sfn|Lloyd|2004}}{{sfn|Spencer|2014|page=14}} Her last surviving brother, Thomas, died in 1269, and she inherited his titles, becoming [[Counts and dukes of Aumale#Aumale in the English peerage|Countess of Aumale]].{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=75}} Her lands fell into King Henry's custody.{{sfn|Spencer|2014|page=28}} However, Aveline died on 10 November 1274 at [[Stockwell]], [[Surrey]],{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=76}} which prevented Edmund from inheriting the lands.{{sfn|Lloyd|2004}} They had no issue.{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=76}}\n\nAveline was buried in [[Westminster Abbey]], the first tomb to be placed in its new church.{{sfn|Weir|2008|p=76}} The historian [[Peter Coss]] has called the tombs of her and [[Eleanor of Castile]] \"two of the finest female effigies of the thirteenth century.\"{{sfn|Coss|1998|page=76}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Works cited\n* {{Cite book |title=Virgin: The Untouched History |first=Hanne |last=Blank |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=2007 |isbn=1596910119 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=The Lady in Medieval England 1000-1500 |first=Peter R. |last=Coss |authorlink=Peter Coss |publisher=Sutton Publishing |year=1998 |isbn=0788197886 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Queens Consort: England's Medieval Queens from Eleanor of Aquitaine to Elizabeth of York |first=Lisa|last=Hilton |publisher=Pegasus Classics|year=2010 |isbn=1605981052 |ref=harv}}\n*{{ODNBweb|last=Lloyd |first=Simon |title=Edmund, first earl of Lancaster and first earl of Leicester (1245\u20131296) |year=2004 |id=8504}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Nobility and Kingship in Medieval England |first=Andrew |last=Spencer |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2014 |isbn=110702675X |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Alison|last=Weir |authorlink=Alison Weir|title=Britain's Royal Families, The Complete Genealogy|publisher=Vintage Books |year=2008 |isbn=978-0099539735 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{succession box | title= [[Earl of Aumale|Countess of Aumale]] | before=[[Thomas de Forz, 4th Earl of Aumale|Thomas de Forz]] | after=''Title defunct'' | years=1269&ndash;1274}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aumale, Aveline de Forz, Countess of}}\n[[Category:1259 births]]\n[[Category:1274 deaths]]\n[[Category:English countesses]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Earls of Albemarle]]\n[[Category:13th-century English people]]\n[[Category:13th-century English women]]\n", "name_user": "GreenComputer", "label": "safe", "comment": "issue -> children", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aveline_de_Forz,_Countess_of_Aumale"}
{"title_page": "The Girl of Your Dreams", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Girl of Your Dreams\n| image          = La ni\u00f1a de tus ojos.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| image_size     = 250px\n| director       = [[Fernando Trueba]]\n| producer       = [[Andr\u00e9s Vicente G\u00f3mez]]<br>[[Eduardo Campoy]]<br>[[Cristina Huete]]\n| writer         = [[Rafael Azcona]]<br>[[Miguel \u00c1ngel Egea]]<br>Carlos L\u00f3pez<br>[[David Trueba]]\n| starring       = [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]]<br>[[Antonio Resines]]<br>[[Jorge Sanz]]<br>[[Rosa Mar\u00eda Sard\u00e0]]<br>[[Santiago Segura]]\n| music          = [[Antoine Duhamel]]\n| cinematography = [[Javier Aguirresarobe]]\n| editing        = [[Carmen Fr\u00edas]]\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1998|11|13}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = Spain\n| language       = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]<br>[[German language|German]]<br>[[Russian language|Russian]]\n| budget         =\n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''The Girl of Your Dreams''''' ({{lang-es|'''La ni\u00f1a de tus ojos'''}}) is a 1998 [[Cinema of Spain|Spanish]] [[drama film]] produced and directed by [[Fernando Trueba]] that stars [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]], [[Antonio Resines]], [[Johannes Silberschneider]] and [[Hanna Schygulla]]. Set during the [[Spanish Civil War]], it centers on a fictional [[Andaluc\u00eda|Andalusian]] actress making a film in [[Nazi Germany]] who becomes the object of [[Joseph Goebbels]]' attentions. \n\n==Plot==\nIn 1938, while Spain is in the grip of [[Spanish Civil War|civil war]], a film team from territory held by [[Francisco Franco|Franco]]'s rebels are invited to the co-production in Berlin of a musical set in 19th-century [[Andalusia|Andalucia]], to be shot in separate Spanish and German versions. At first happy to be working away from their war-torn country, the group find life under [[Nazism]] increasingly unpleasant and dangerous. \n\nMacarena, their attractive star, soon catches the eye of [[Joseph Goebbels|Goebbels]], the [[Minister of Public Enlightenment and Propaganda]], who is determined to bed her. Though she finds him repulsive, and prefers the company of Blas, the married director of the Spanish version, it is made clear to her that for the sake of the project and of Hispano-German relations she must comply.\n\nWhen she points out that the extras in the film look ridiculously inauthentic, being tall and fair-haired, they are replaced by short dark [[Jews|Jewish]] and [[Romani people|Romani]] prisoners from a [[Nazi concentration camps|concentration camp]], under armed [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] guards. An extra with whom she sympathises, a handsome Russian called Leo, escapes the guards and she smuggles him into the villa where Goebbels has installed her. When Goebbels calls round, Leo knocks him out cold.\n\nBlas realises that this is the end of the road for the project and rushes to see Goebbels' [[Magda Goebbels|wife]], who is well aware of her husband's activities. She writes him a pass enabling Leo, Macarena and her dresser to board a plane that night. The fate of the rest of the group, who are all under arrest, is unclear.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]] as Macarena Granada\n* [[Antonio Resines]] as Blas Fontiveros\n* [[Jorge Sanz]] as Juli\u00e1n Torralba\n* [[Rosa Maria Sard\u00e0]] as Rosa Rosales\n* [[Santiago Segura]] as Castillo\n* [[Loles Le\u00f3n]] as Trini Morenos\n* [[Jes\u00fas Bonilla]] as Marco Bonilla\n* [[Neus Asensi]] as Lucia Gandia\n* [[Miroslav T\u00e1borsk\u00fd]] as V\u00e1clav Passer\n* [[Johannes Silberschneider]] as [[Joseph Goebbels|Goebbels]]\n* [[Karel Dobry]] as Leo\n* [[G\u00f6tz Otto]] as Heinrich von Wermelskirch\n* [[Hanna Schygulla]] as [[Magda Goebbels]]\n* [[Mar\u00eda Barranco]] as Ambassador's wife\n* [[Juan Luis Galiardo]] as Ambassador\n\n== Historical background ==\nDuring the Civil War, filmmakers from the Nationalist side found work in Germany and Italy. For example, in 1938 at the [[Universum Film AG|UFA]] studios in [[Babelsberg Studio|Babelsberg]], the Spanish director [[Flori\u00e1n Rey]] filmed ''[[Carmen, la de Triana]]'' in Spanish and a German version called ''[[Andalusische N\u00e4chte]]'', both starring the [[Argentina|Argentine]] singer and actress [[Imperio Argentina]] with whom, according to legend, [[Hitler]] fell in love. She is reported to have sued the producers and director for using her life story without permission.\n==Accolades==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Award / Film Festival\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"18\"| 1999\n| rowspan=\"17\"| [[13th Goya Awards|1999 Goya Awards]]\n| Best Film\n| The Girl of Your Dreams\n| {{win}}\n| rowspan=\"17\"|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premiosgoya.com/13-edicion/premios/por-categoria/|title=Ganadores Premios Goya 1999|work=Academia del Cine|access-date=2020-04-04|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premiosgoya.com/13-edicion/nominaciones/por-categoria/|title=Nominados Premios Goya 1999|work=Academia del Cine|access-date=2020-04-04|language=es}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Director\n| Fernando Trueba\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actor\n| Antonio Resines\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actress\n| Pen\u00e9lope Cruz\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| Jorge Sanz\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| Rosa Maria Sard\u00e1\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Original Screenplay\n| Miguel \u00c1ngel Egea and Carlos L\u00f3pez\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best New Actor\n| Miroslav T\u00e1borsk\u00fd\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Javier Aguirresarobe\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Editing\n| Iv\u00e1n Aledo\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Art Direction\n| Gerardo Vera\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Production Supervision\n| Ang\u00e9lica Huete\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Sound\n| Pierre Gamet, Dominique Hennequin & Santiago Th\u00e9venet\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Special Effects\n| Emilio Ruiz & Alfonso Nieto\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Costume Design\n| Sonia Grande & Lala Huete\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Makeup and Hairstlyes\n| Antonio Panizza & Gregorio Ros\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Original Score\n| Antoine Duhamel\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[49th Berlin International Film Festival|1999 Berlin International Film Festival]]\n| Golden Bear\n| The Girl of Your Dreams\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\"|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/archive/jahresarchive/1999/02_programm_1999/02_programm_1999.html|title=Berlinale: 1999 Programme |accessdate=2012-02-02 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Sequel==\nA sequel, ''[[La reina de Espa\u00f1a]]'' (English: The Queen of Spain), starring [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]] and [[Jorge Sanz]], was released on 25 November 2016.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0158030|title=La ni\u00f1a de tus ojos}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|girl_of_your_dreams}}\n\n{{Goya Award for Best Film}}\n{{Fernando Trueba}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl Of Your Dreams, The}}\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:1998 films]]\n[[Category:Best Film Goya Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films about filmmaking]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Fernando Trueba]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Goya Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films set in Berlin]]\n[[Category:Films set in Germany]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1939]]\n[[Category:German-language films]]\n[[Category:Russian-language films]]\n[[Category:Spanish Civil War films]]\n[[Category:Spanish films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Rafael Azcona]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Babelsberg Studios]]\n{{1990s-Spain-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Girl of Your Dreams\n| image          = La ni\u00f1a de tus ojos.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| image_size     = 250px\n| director       = [[Fernando Trueba]]\n| producer       = [[Andr\u00e9s Vicente G\u00f3mez]]<br>[[Eduardo Campoy]]<br>[[Cristina Huete]]\n| writer         = [[Rafael Azcona]]<br>[[Miguel \u00c1ngel Egea]]<br>Carlos L\u00f3pez<br>[[David Trueba]]\n| starring       = [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]]<br>[[Antonio Resines]]<br>[[Jorge Sanz]]<br>[[Rosa Mar\u00eda Sard\u00e0]]<br>[[Santiago Segura]]\n| music          = [[Antoine Duhamel]]\n| cinematography = [[Javier Aguirresarobe]]\n| editing        = [[Carmen Fr\u00edas]]\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1998|11|13}}\n| runtime        = 121 minutes\n| country        = Spain\n| language       = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]<br>[[German language|German]]<br>[[Russian language|Russian]]\n| budget         =\n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''The Girl of Your Dreams''''' ({{lang-es|'''La ni\u00f1a de tus ojos'''}}) is a 1998 [[Cinema of Spain|Spanish]] [[drama film]] produced and directed by [[Fernando Trueba]] that stars [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]], [[Antonio Resines]], [[Johannes Silberschneider]] and [[Hanna Schygulla]]. Set during the [[Spanish Civil War]], it centers on a fictional [[Andaluc\u00eda|Andalusian]] actress making a film in [[Nazi Germany]] who becomes the object of [[Joseph Goebbels]]' attentions. \n\n==Plot==\nIn 1938, while Spain is in the grip of [[Spanish Civil War|civil war]], a film team from territory held by [[Francisco Franco|Franco]]'s rebels are invited to the co-production in Berlin of a musical set in 19th-century [[Andalusia|Andalucia]], to be shot in separate Spanish and German versions. At first happy to be working away from their war-torn country, the group find life under [[Nazism]] increasingly unpleasant and dangerous. \n\nMacarena, their attractive star, soon catches the eye of [[Joseph Goebbels|Goebbels]], the [[Minister of Public Enlightenment and Propaganda]], who is determined to bed her. Though she finds him repulsive, and prefers the company of Blas, the married director of the Spanish version, it is made clear to her that for the sake of the project and of Hispano-German relations she must comply.\n\nWhen she points out that the extras in the film look ridiculously inauthentic, being tall and fair-haired, they are replaced by short dark [[Jews|Jewish]] and [[Romani people|Romani]] prisoners from a [[Nazi concentration camps|concentration camp]], under armed [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] guards. An extra with whom she sympathises, a handsome Russian called Leo, escapes the guards and she smuggles him into the villa where Goebbels has installed her. When Goebbels calls round, Leo knocks him out cold.\n\nBlas realises that this is the end of the road for the project and rushes to see Goebbels' [[Magda Goebbels|wife]], who is well aware of her husband's activities. She writes him a pass enabling Leo, Macarena and her dresser to board a plane that night. The fate of the rest of the group, who are all under arrest, is unclear.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]] as Macarena Granada\n* [[Antonio Resines]] as Blas Fontiveros\n* [[Jorge Sanz]] as Juli\u00e1n Torralba\n* [[Rosa Maria Sard\u00e0]] as Rosa Rosales\n* [[Santiago Segura]] as Castillo\n* [[Loles Le\u00f3n]] as Trini Morenos\n* [[Jes\u00fas Bonilla]] as Marco Bonilla\n* [[Neus Asensi]] as Lucia Gandia\n* [[Miroslav T\u00e1borsk\u00fd]] as V\u00e1clav Passer\n* [[Johannes Silberschneider]] as [[Joseph Goebbels|Goebbels]]\n* [[Karel Dobry]] as Leo\n* [[G\u00f6tz Otto]] as Heinrich von Wermelskirch\n* [[Hanna Schygulla]] as [[Magda Goebbels]]\n* [[Mar\u00eda Barranco]] as Ambassador's wife\n* [[Juan Luis Galiardo]] as Ambassador\n\n== Historical background ==\nDuring the Civil War, filmmakers from the Nationalist side found work in Germany and Italy. For example, in 1938 at the [[Universum Film AG|UFA]] studios in [[Babelsberg Studio|Babelsberg]], the Spanish director [[Flori\u00e1n Rey]] filmed ''[[Carmen, la de Triana]]'' in Spanish and a German version called ''[[Andalusische N\u00e4chte]]'', both starring the [[Argentina|Argentine]] singer and actress [[Imperio Argentina]] with whom, according to legend, [[Hitler]] fell in love. She is reported to have sued the producers and director for using her life story without permission.\n==Accolades==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Award / Film Festival\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"18\"| 1999\n| rowspan=\"17\"| [[13th Goya Awards|1999 Goya Awards]]\n| Best Film\n| The Girl of Your Dreams\n| {{win}}\n| rowspan=\"17\"|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premiosgoya.com/13-edicion/premios/por-categoria/|title=Ganadores Premios Goya 1999|work=Academia del Cine|access-date=2020-04-04|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premiosgoya.com/13-edicion/nominaciones/por-categoria/|title=Nominados Premios Goya 1999|work=Academia del Cine|access-date=2020-04-04|language=es}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Director\n| Fernando Trueba\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actor\n| Antonio Resines\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actress\n| Pen\u00e9lope Cruz\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| Jorge Sanz\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| Rosa Maria Sard\u00e1\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Original Screenplay\n| Miguel \u00c1ngel Egea and Carlos L\u00f3pez\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best New Actor\n| Miroslav T\u00e1borsk\u00fd\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Javier Aguirresarobe\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Editing\n| Iv\u00e1n Aledo\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Art Direction\n| Gerardo Vera\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Production Supervision\n| Ang\u00e9lica Huete\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Best Sound\n| Pierre Gamet, Dominique Hennequin & Santiago Th\u00e9venet\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Special Effects\n| Emilio Ruiz & Alfonso Nieto\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Costume Design\n| Sonia Grande & Lala 